00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:27.910
So let's start
with in-home usage.

00:07:27.910 --> 00:07:31.280
Smart speakers have been used
in the home for a few years now.

00:07:31.280 --> 00:07:33.700
So when we look
at in-home usage,

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:35.770
data shows that
it's becoming part

00:07:35.770 --> 00:07:39.310
of people's everyday routines.

00:07:39.310 --> 00:07:40.930
In a study we
conducted, we wanted

00:07:40.930 --> 00:07:43.660
to understand how digital
assistants were being

00:07:43.660 --> 00:07:45.310
embedded in people's lives.

00:07:45.310 --> 00:07:48.610
We asked users to think
about their everyday routines

00:07:48.610 --> 00:07:51.520
and think of the user
digital assistants in them.

00:07:51.520 --> 00:07:54.790
If they answered yes,
we then asked them how.

00:07:54.790 --> 00:07:58.030
What we found is that 89%
of respondents told us

00:07:58.030 --> 00:08:00.130
they were leveraging
their digital assistants

00:08:00.130 --> 00:08:04.070
during their daily routines
for multiple activities morning

00:08:04.070 --> 00:08:04.960
through night.

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:09.830
And for some, it's even
becoming second nature.

00:08:09.830 --> 00:08:12.110
We found that the three
most common routines

00:08:12.110 --> 00:08:14.030
are happening in the home.

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:18.170
57% say they use their digital
assistants around the house

00:08:18.170 --> 00:08:19.280
while relaxing.

00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:22.520
So this could be anything like
playing a game or streaming

00:08:22.520 --> 00:08:24.830
music after a long day's work.

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:27.710
43% say they use their digital
assistants when they're

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:29.190
getting ready in the morning.

00:08:29.190 --> 00:08:32.510
So as people are multitasking,
making breakfast, getting

00:08:32.510 --> 00:08:36.289
ready, they're also asking their
digital assistants for commute

00:08:36.289 --> 00:08:38.840
information, for the
news, for the weather,

00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:40.880
or maybe preordering
a cup of coffee

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:42.820
before they walk out the door.

00:08:42.820 --> 00:08:46.730
And last 43% also say that they
use their digital assistant

00:08:46.730 --> 00:08:48.310
when they're
planning their week.

00:08:48.310 --> 00:08:51.710
Here we're seeing people
setting reminders,

00:08:51.710 --> 00:08:55.730
adding calendar invites for
things later in the week.

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:57.530
They're researching
locations that they're

00:08:57.530 --> 00:08:59.210
considering going to.

00:08:59.210 --> 00:09:02.730
And sometimes even booking
restaurant reservations.

00:09:02.730 --> 00:09:04.400
A quote like the
one you see here

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:06.440
is actually something
common we heard

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:08.360
when we were going
into the homes

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:10.310
of digital assistant
users and asking them

00:09:10.310 --> 00:09:11.750
about their day-to-day.

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:13.640
They would say, my
digital assistant

00:09:13.640 --> 00:09:15.680
is part of my daily routine.

00:09:15.680 --> 00:09:18.035
I come down to the
kitchen, turn on my coffee,

00:09:18.035 --> 00:09:19.910
and ask my digital
assistant for the weather.

00:09:22.350 --> 00:09:24.100
MEI LU: These numbers,
percentage numbers,

00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:27.500
are actually pretty
encouraging to me personally.

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:32.060
I was reading an article, a
recent paper about the adoption

00:09:32.060 --> 00:09:33.500
of the internet.

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:36.530
The researchers said
it's the small things

00:09:36.530 --> 00:09:41.230
that people use the internet
for on the everyday basis that

00:09:41.230 --> 00:09:44.490
make it an integral
part of people's life.

00:09:44.490 --> 00:09:46.910
Then they become indispensable.

00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:50.330
We once invited 32
users to our lab

00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:55.340
and observed how they use
different type of actions.

00:09:55.340 --> 00:09:57.570
In the study, our
users were indeed

00:09:57.570 --> 00:10:01.190
telling us they have been
using digital assistants

00:10:01.190 --> 00:10:04.490
on the daily basis, often
times for small things,

00:10:04.490 --> 00:10:06.800
just like weather.

00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:10.640
Those small things are
entwined with many other things

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:13.800
they're doing at home.

00:10:13.800 --> 00:10:18.090
Now, how should we design
the most engaging actions

00:10:18.090 --> 00:10:22.500
for people's homes
that can be embedded

00:10:22.500 --> 00:10:26.020
into people's daily routines?

00:10:26.020 --> 00:10:29.540
After the first
encounter, it actually

00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:32.230
needs to meet the
user expectations.

00:10:32.230 --> 00:10:37.280
In our lab studies, we can see
user will very quickly abandon

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:42.000
action if they cannot easily
figure out how to use it.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:45.460
The first step, oh,
how can I use this?

00:10:45.460 --> 00:10:47.290
Then they also
carry expectations

00:10:47.290 --> 00:10:50.910
for brands they are
already familiar with.

00:10:50.910 --> 00:10:56.020
An example would be if it says
TED or CNN talk or action,

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:59.440
then they very much
expect to see videos

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:01.330
on the smart display.

00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:05.320
If they are already using
your services on the web

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:08.560
or on mobile apps, at
this first encounter

00:11:08.560 --> 00:11:12.220
they expect to see some
familiarity, some familiar

00:11:12.220 --> 00:11:16.080
things that you get things done.

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:21.420
So if we order a
pizza or a car ride,

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:24.810
at that first moment,
encounter moment,

00:11:24.810 --> 00:11:27.960
you do not want the user to
feel any kind of disappointment

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:32.730
or they feel they're
totally lost.

00:11:32.730 --> 00:11:38.640
Then for next steps,
users will try to assess,

00:11:38.640 --> 00:11:42.420
does this action provide
the right utility or values?

00:11:42.420 --> 00:11:45.160
Is this something I want to use?

00:11:45.160 --> 00:11:48.510
We find that users carry the
mental model of a signature

00:11:48.510 --> 00:11:53.420
functionality--
signature functionality,

00:11:53.420 --> 00:11:56.400
especially for brands
they are familiar with.

00:11:56.400 --> 00:12:00.050
So for example, our research
colleagues in Google Maps teams

00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:04.910
studied the user interaction
for Google Maps and ways

00:12:04.910 --> 00:12:07.130
through assistant.

00:12:07.130 --> 00:12:08.540
Those are similar apps.

00:12:08.540 --> 00:12:11.060
We know they provide
similar functionalities.

00:12:11.060 --> 00:12:16.190
But for Google Maps, the
user's signature functionality

00:12:16.190 --> 00:12:19.310
is to ask for directions.

00:12:19.310 --> 00:12:26.590
Then switched away, it becomes
to report accident via voice.

00:12:26.590 --> 00:12:29.980
So I know many of you
probably focus on voice only.

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:33.730
You're creating brand new
experience on this platform.

00:12:33.730 --> 00:12:36.160
Then signature
functionality is something

00:12:36.160 --> 00:12:40.000
that will get a user excited.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.090
That's something they
want to talk about.

00:12:42.090 --> 00:12:44.680
Or it will have
captured attention

00:12:44.680 --> 00:12:49.258
from maybe on social media
or from the product emails

00:12:49.258 --> 00:12:50.050
they have received.

00:12:52.940 --> 00:12:56.370
Some experiences are designed
across multiple devices.

00:12:56.370 --> 00:12:59.420
Users can start from smart
speakers, for example,

00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:02.360
then continue onto
mobile phones.

00:13:02.360 --> 00:13:05.720
But for signature
functionality, do not do that.

00:13:05.720 --> 00:13:08.870
Breaking it across multiple
devices will break the flow

00:13:08.870 --> 00:13:10.640
and violate user trust.

00:13:13.220 --> 00:13:17.900
Users definitely then
compare what they have--

00:13:17.900 --> 00:13:21.120
compare action to what
they have on other devices,

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:23.660
especially on the mobile app.

00:13:23.660 --> 00:13:26.630
They appreciate the actions
that provide convenience

00:13:26.630 --> 00:13:28.730
beyond those solutions.

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:30.605
At this stage, we
see really they

00:13:30.605 --> 00:13:34.280
are attracted to
quick solutions that

00:13:34.280 --> 00:13:38.770
allow them to get things done,
especially when hands free.

00:13:38.770 --> 00:13:45.850
So for this example, this user
has lived in different states

00:13:45.850 --> 00:13:47.880
and he wants to keep
up with what's going on

00:13:47.880 --> 00:13:49.610
in all those different places.

00:13:49.610 --> 00:13:53.050
Then the radio action
allows him really

00:13:53.050 --> 00:13:57.880
to easily get to those
stations just by saying

00:13:57.880 --> 00:14:00.960
the name of the stations.

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:04.600
Overall, we need to
create aha moments.

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:07.730
And the users see it,
oh, that's interesting.

00:14:07.730 --> 00:14:09.820
And then I want
to give it a try.

00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:12.520
And they immediately
say, oh, this

00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:15.750
is better than what I
have on other devices.

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:22.880
Navigation-- navigation
with voice only

00:14:22.880 --> 00:14:26.180
or now with a combination
of the voice and the visuals

00:14:26.180 --> 00:14:28.170
are still very new.

00:14:28.170 --> 00:14:30.710
It's very common
for users to find

00:14:30.710 --> 00:14:34.950
it hard to talk to
digital assistants.

